        <section id="ahdb" class="mb-12 scroll-mt-24">
          <h2 class="font-display text-3xl text-navy mb-4">What does AHDB Dairy 2024 say about cubicle sizing?</h2>
          <p class="text-cast-700 text-lg leading-relaxed mb-4">
            <strong class="text-navy">AHDB Dairy's 2024 housing guidance ties cubicle dimensions to cow size — specifically wither
            height and diagonal body length — rather than treating "Holstein" or "Jersey" as a single number.</strong>
            For a 650kg Holstein the recommendation is 2.4m total length, 1.2m centre-to-centre width,
            neck rail at 1.15m and brisket board 1.7m from the kerb.
          </p>
          <p class="text-cast-700 text-lg leading-relaxed mb-4">
            The numbers come from welfare research showing cows lunge forward 0.6–0.9m when rising and
            need a clear bed length of around 1.8m to lie comfortably with their legs tucked. Cubicles
            sized for an "average" 1990s Holstein (typically 2.2m × 1.1m) are now too small for modern
            Holsteins which routinely weigh 700kg+ and stand 1.45m at the wither.
          </p>
          <p class="text-cast-700 text-lg leading-relaxed">
            The guidance is welfare-led but ties directly to commercial outcomes: cows in undersized
            cubicles spend less time lying, drop yield (around 1.5 litres per hour of lying-time lost),
            and develop more hock and knee lesions. Sizing is one of the cheapest yield levers a dairy
            unit has. WCCP precast <a href="/products/cattle-cubicles" class="text-ember underline">cubicle beds</a>,
            <a href="/products/cubicle-end-walls" class="text-ember underline">cubicle end walls</a>,
            <a href="/products/heelstone-coping" class="text-ember underline">heelstone coping</a>
            and <a href="/products/water-troughs" class="text-ember underline">water troughs</a> are
            cast to AHDB 2024 dimensions across the
            <a href="/sectors/agricultural" class="text-ember underline">agricultural sector</a>.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="breed-table" class="mb-12 scroll-mt-24">
          <h2 class="font-display text-3xl text-navy mb-4">What are the cubicle dimensions for each breed?</h2>
          <p class="text-cast-700 text-lg leading-relaxed mb-6">
            <strong class="text-navy">Holstein-Friesian: 2.4m × 1.2m. Jersey: 2.2m × 1.1m. Beef suckler (medium): 2.4m × 1.2m.
            Continental beef: 2.5m × 1.25m. Heifers: scale 90% of mature herd dimensions.</strong>
            The width given is centre-to-centre between divisions; the bed itself is 50–80mm narrower
            once division thickness is accounted for.
          </p>

          <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-4 -mx-4 sm:mx-0">
            <table class="spec-table min-w-full px-4 sm:px-0">
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Breed / type</th>
                  <th>Length</th>
                  <th>Width (c/c)</th>
                  <th>Neck rail height</th>
                  <th>Brisket board</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody class="text-cast">
                <tr>
                  <td>Holstein-Friesian (650kg)</td>
                  <td><strong class="text-navy">2.40m</strong></td>
                  <td><strong class="text-navy">1.20m</strong></td>
                  <td>1.15m</td>
                  <td>1.70m from kerb</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Holstein (large, 750kg+)</td>
                  <td><strong class="text-navy">2.50m</strong></td>
                  <td><strong class="text-navy">1.25m</strong></td>
                  <td>1.20m</td>
                  <td>1.75m from kerb</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Jersey (450kg)</td>
                  <td><strong class="text-navy">2.20m</strong></td>
                  <td><strong class="text-navy">1.10m</strong></td>
                  <td>1.05m</td>
                  <td>1.55m from kerb</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Crossbreed (Holstein × Jersey)</td>
                  <td><strong class="text-navy">2.30m</strong></td>
                  <td><strong class="text-navy">1.15m</strong></td>
                  <td>1.10m</td>
                  <td>1.60m from kerb</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Beef suckler (medium frame)</td>
                  <td><strong class="text-navy">2.40m</strong></td>
                  <td><strong class="text-navy">1.20m</strong></td>
                  <td>1.20m</td>
                  <td>1.70m from kerb</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Continental beef (Limousin, Charolais)</td>
                  <td><strong class="text-navy">2.50m</strong></td>
                  <td><strong class="text-navy">1.25m</strong></td>
                  <td>1.25m</td>
                  <td>1.80m from kerb</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Dairy heifers (in calf)</td>
                  <td><strong class="text-navy">2.20m</strong></td>
                  <td><strong class="text-navy">1.10m</strong></td>
                  <td>1.05m</td>
                  <td>1.55m from kerb</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
          <p class="text-sm text-cast italic">
            All dimensions to AHDB Dairy 2024 housing guidance. Add 50mm bedding allowance for sand or
            deep-bed mattresses.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="bodyweight" class="mb-12 scroll-mt-24">
          <h2 class="font-display text-3xl text-navy mb-4">How does body weight change cubicle dimensions?</h2>
          <p class="text-cast-700 text-lg leading-relaxed mb-4">
            <strong class="text-navy">As a rule of thumb, cubicle length should equal 1.83 × hook bone height,
            and cubicle width should be 0.83 × hook bone height. For a 650kg Holstein with a 1.30m hook
            bone height, that gives 2.38m × 1.08m — close to the 2.4m × 1.2m standard once a small margin
            is added for movement.</strong>
          </p>
          <p class="text-cast-700 text-lg leading-relaxed mb-4">
            Modern dairy genetics have added 50–80kg of mature weight per decade since the 1980s. A
            1990s Holstein at 600kg fitted comfortably in a 2.3m × 1.15m cubicle. Today's 720kg cow
            doesn't, and you'll see her lying diagonally, dunging on the rear of the bed, or refusing
            to enter at all.
          </p>
          <p class="text-cast-700 text-lg leading-relaxed">
            We recommend measuring 10 representative cows in your herd — wither height, hook bone
            height and diagonal body length — before specifying a new cubicle row. The five-minute
            measurement saves a £30,000 mistake.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="neck-rail" class="mb-12 scroll-mt-24">
          <h2 class="font-display text-3xl text-navy mb-4">How high should the neck rail be?</h2>
          <p class="text-cast-700 text-lg leading-relaxed mb-4">
            <strong class="text-navy">Set the neck rail at 0.83 × wither height — 1.15m for a typical Holstein,
            1.05m for a Jersey, 1.20m–1.25m for Continental beef. Position it 1.7m forward of the rear
            kerb (or matched to the brisket board distance for the breed).</strong>
            The rail's job is to position the cow when she enters so she dungs in the passage, not
            on the bed.
          </p>
          <p class="text-cast-700 text-lg leading-relaxed mb-4">
            Too low and the cow refuses to enter — you'll see chains of cows queuing in the passage
            with the cubicles empty. Too high and she stands half-in, dunging on the front of the bed.
            The "knee test" works: a cow should be able to stand square in the cubicle with her front
            knees on the bed and her hocks just inside the rear kerb.
          </p>
          <p class="text-cast-700 text-lg leading-relaxed">
            All WCCP cubicle divisions ship with adjustable neck rails on a swedge tube fixing.
            Typical adjustment range is ±100mm in 25mm increments, which covers most herd shifts.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="brisket-board" class="mb-12 scroll-mt-24">
          <h2 class="font-display text-3xl text-navy mb-4">Where does the brisket board go?</h2>
          <p class="text-cast-700 text-lg leading-relaxed mb-4">
            <strong class="text-navy">The brisket board sits 1.7m from the rear kerb for a Holstein, 1.55m for
            a Jersey, 1.75–1.8m for Continental beef. Maximum height 100mm above the bed, with a
            radiused or chamfered top edge.</strong> Its purpose is to control where the cow's chest
            rests — pushing her hindquarters back so she dungs in the passage.
          </p>
          <p class="text-cast-700 text-lg leading-relaxed mb-4">
            Common mistakes: too high (causes hock lesions on rising), too sharp (knee abrasions),
            too far back (cow over-shoots and lies with chest in the lunge space), or no board at all
            (cow drifts forward and dungs on the bed). A 100mm precast board with a 25mm radius edge
            is the AHDB-aligned standard.
          </p>
          <p class="text-cast-700 text-lg leading-relaxed">
            We supply brisket boards either cast integrally with the bed (deep-bed sand systems) or
            as bolt-down precast strips (mattress and rubber-mat systems). The bolt-down version
            allows seasonal adjustment for in-calf heifers joining the milking herd.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="lunge-space" class="mb-12 scroll-mt-24">
          <h2 class="font-display text-3xl text-navy mb-4">How much lunge space does a cow need?</h2>
          <p class="text-cast-700 text-lg leading-relaxed mb-4">
            <strong class="text-navy">A cow needs 0.6m–0.9m of unobstructed lunge space forward of the brisket
            board. For an open-fronted cubicle that means 0.6m clear to a wall; for head-to-head pairs
            the total cubicle-to-cubicle length should be 4.8m (for Holsteins) so each cow has
            unobstructed lunge into the opposing cubicle.</strong>
          </p>
          <p class="text-cast-700 text-lg leading-relaxed mb-4">
            Cattle don't rise like horses. They throw their heads forward and downward to shift their
            centre of gravity, then heave the hindquarters up, then the front. Block that head movement
            with a wall, gate or solid head rail and the cow can't rise — she'll either refuse to lie
            or struggle when she does, increasing injury risk.
          </p>
          <p class="text-cast-700 text-lg leading-relaxed">
            Open-fronted (against an outside wall) and head-to-head (paired) layouts both work.
            Avoid forward-blocked layouts — sometimes seen in retrofitted older buildings — unless
            you can guarantee 1.0m+ of clear lunge space in front.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="mistakes" class="mb-12 scroll-mt-24">
          <h2 class="font-display text-3xl text-navy mb-4">What are the 5 most common cubicle sizing mistakes?</h2>
          <p class="text-cast-700 text-lg leading-relaxed mb-4">
            <strong class="text-navy">In order of frequency: cubicles too short for modern Holsteins, neck rail
            too low or too far back, brisket board too high, head-to-head pairs only 4.5m total, and
            mixing dairy and dry cow groups in the same cubicle size.</strong>
            Each one shaves litres off yield or adds vet bills.
          </p>
          <ul class="text-cast-700 text-lg leading-relaxed space-y-3 list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
            <li><strong class="text-navy">Old beds, new cows.</strong> A 2.2m bed designed for 1995 Holsteins is too short for 2026 Holsteins. Measure your cows.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-navy">Neck rail set for an empty bed.</strong> Add bedding depth to the height. A 50mm sand or mattress depth means the rail is effectively 50mm lower than spec.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-navy">Brisket board too tall.</strong> Above 100mm the board catches the cow's foreleg as she rises. We see hock lesions in herds with 150mm timber boards.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-navy">Head-to-head too short.</strong> 4.5m total isn't enough for two Holsteins to lunge. Specify 4.8m, or 5.0m for large-frame herds.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-navy">One size for all groups.</strong> Heifers, dry cows and milkers don't fit one size. Group sizing increases lying time and yield in every benchmarked study.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section id="checklist" class="mb-12 scroll-mt-24">
          <h2 class="font-display text-3xl text-navy mb-4">Cubicle sizing checklist (10 points)</h2>
          <p class="text-cast-700 text-lg leading-relaxed mb-6">
            <strong class="text-navy">Tick all ten and your cubicles will pass the AHDB welfare audit and
            maximise lying time. Most issues we see on farm visits are one of these ten items.</strong>
          </p>
          <div class="bg-bone-200 border-l-4 border-ember p-6 rounded-r">
            <ol class="text-cast-700 text-base leading-relaxed space-y-3 list-decimal pl-5">
              <li>Measured 10 representative cows for wither height and diagonal body length</li>
              <li>Cubicle length matched to breed (2.4m Holstein, 2.2m Jersey, 2.5m Continental beef)</li>
              <li>Cubicle width centre-to-centre matched to breed (1.10m–1.25m)</li>
              <li>Neck rail at 0.83 × wither height (1.05m–1.25m typical)</li>
              <li>Brisket board 1.55m–1.80m from rear kerb, max 100mm tall, radiused edge</li>
              <li>0.6m+ clear lunge space forward, or 4.8m head-to-head total</li>
              <li>Bedding depth allowance added to neck rail and brisket board calculation</li>
              <li>Heifer / dry cow / milker groups sized separately where housed in different rows</li>
              <li>Adjustable neck rail fixings for seasonal or breed shifts</li>
              <li>Passage width minimum 3.0m behind cubicles for cow flow and scraper clearance</li>
            </ol>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section id="faq" class="mb-12 scroll-mt-24">
          <h2 class="font-display text-3xl text-navy mb-6">Frequently asked questions</h2>
          <div class="space-y-4">
            {faqs.map((f) => (
